ging together findings from a range a fields, from development economics and development studies to political science and sociology, The Institutional Foundation of Economic Development explores the precise mechanisms through which institutions affect growth.Shiping Tang contends institutions shape economic development through four “Big Things”: possibility, incentive, capability, and opportunity. From this perspective, IFED has six major dimensions: political hierarchy, property rights, social mobility, redistribution, innovation protection, and equal opportunity. Tang further argues that IFED is only one pillar within the New Development Triangle (NDT): sustained economic development also requires strong state capacity and sound socioeconomic policies.Arguing for an evolutionary approach tied to a country’s stage of development, The Institutional Foundation of Economic Development advances an understanding of institutions and economic development through a holistic, interdisciplinary lens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEconomic development. 0aInstitutional economics. 0aPolitical stabilityxEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Economic Development.2bisacsh  aAggregate demand.  aAutocracy.  aBasic education.  aBond Yield.  aBureau of Economic Analysis.  aCapital accumulation.  aCapital control.  aCapital market.  aClassical economics.  aConsumer behaviour.  aConsumer spending.  aConsumer.  aConsumption (economics).  aConvergence (economics).  aCost Of Funds.  aCredit default swap.  aCredit risk.  aCurrency.  aCurrent account.  aDemocracy and economic growth.  aDerivative (finance).  aDeveloped country.  aDevelopment economics.  aEconomic development.  aEconomic equilibrium.  aEconomic growth.  aEconomic history.  aEconomic indicator.  